{"actual_usd":0.158585,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":352,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, gathering the plainest way to say it.* \"The death was real.\"\n\n\"If Jesus only seemed to die, then we're not saved by a real cross but by a kind of holy stage trick, and the New Testament just won't let you do that. Christians have always had to say two things at once: God the Son truly took on flesh, and in that flesh he truly suffered and died. Not that the divine nature blinked out, and not that a mere human shell was left behind to absorb the pain alone.\"\n\n*I rub at my jaw, thinking of how often people try to protect God by thinning out the Incarnation until it stops costing anything.* \"You're putting your finger on a real old controversy. Some did say the Christ only appeared to suffer, or that the divine Christ departed before the crucifixion. But the church rejected that because it breaks the heart of the gospel. The one who died on the cross is the same person who is the eternal Son. He died according to his human nature, not according to the divine nature as though God ceased to be God.\"\n\n\"That's the careful sentence: God cannot die in his divinity, but Jesus Christ—the God-man—really died. His human soul and body were parted in death, as happens in true human death, and yet the person undergoing that death was truly the Son.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"It's a mystery, yes, but not a fake.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can also show you why the 'divinity left the body' idea sounds tempting for about ten minutes and then starts wrecking everything.\"","rolling_24h_usd":68.83583499999999,"run_id":"8da81a09-3031-4369-a666-8abd405137d0"}
